  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1944561140" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1944561140" />
    <a title="Bernardo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/40481325-bernardo"><img alt="Bernardo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1592868507p2/40481325.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1944561140?book_show_action=true">Nov 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bernardo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bernardo" href="/user/show/40481325-bernardo">Bernardo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781473217386" href="/book/show/33035581-neuromancer">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/40481325-bernardo?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/40481325-bernardo?shelf=dystopian">dystopian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1944561140" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7219295400980990496">Neuromancer was the book that started the cyberpunk movement. It was also in this book that William Gibson coined the term ‘cyberspace’. From cyberspace came the matrix and Neuromancer ended up becoming an influential science fiction book. Besides that, it was the first book to win the three big awards of science fiction: the Nebula, the Hugo and the Philip K. Dick awards.<br/><br/>This book isn’t as accessible as some other science fiction books. You are thrown right into the action of Night City, with i</span>
  <span id="freeText7219295400980990496" style="display:none">Neuromancer was the book that started the cyberpunk movement. It was also in this book that William Gibson coined the term ‘cyberspace’. From cyberspace came the matrix and Neuromancer ended up becoming an influential science fiction book. Besides that, it was the first book to win the three big awards of science fiction: the Nebula, the Hugo and the Philip K. Dick awards.<br /><br />This book isn’t as accessible as some other science fiction books. You are thrown right into the action of Night City, with its drugs, crime, slang and culture. From the start of the book there’s barely anything that even comes close to exposition and you might become a bit bewildered with the dystopian world of Neuromancer. Sometimes, when I wanted something to be clearer it actually became more obscure. This may be due to the fact that the world Gibson is presenting is so different, ever changing and full of new definitions and terms. And similarly, his language and style are also different.<br /><br />The plot is full of intricate features and will keep you interested with its twists and turns, becoming clearer as the story goes on. Speaking of the plot, it’s always moving forward with momentum, especially in the first chapters, as we are introduced to the world and characters of Neuromancer. But what really sets this plot apart from other books is the setting created by Gibson, along with his use of language and style. In particular, I thought his descriptions of cyberspace to be the highest point of his writing. At times the book’s style actually reminded me of the movie Blade Runner and I’m fairly convinced that it influenced Gibson. By now, it may seem that at first I’m complaining about Gibson’s style, only to praise it later. It’s actually a bit of both.<br /><br />Neuromancer may not be everyone’s coffee and it might cause some kind of bewilderment with many new terms and definitions that keep on being introduced, but if you accept the ride you will eventually get used to it, understand it and be rewarded with a great book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7219295400980990496" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

